<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate calories per 100g?", answer: "Divide the total calories by the weight in grams, then multiply by 100. For example, if a 250g serving of pasta has 350 calories, the calories per 100g is (350 / 250) x 100 = 140 calories per 100g. This standardized measure makes it easy to compare the calorie density of different foods regardless of portion size." },
  { question: "What is energy density and why does it matter?", answer: "Energy density is the number of calories per gram or per 100 grams of food. Foods with very low energy density (under 60 cal/100g) like most fruits and vegetables let you eat larger portions for fewer calories. Low density foods (60-150 cal/100g) include lean proteins and cooked grains. Medium density (150-400 cal/100g) includes bread and cheese. High density (above 400 cal/100g) includes nuts, oils, and chocolate. Choosing lower density foods helps with weight management because they provide more volume and satiety per calorie." },
  { question: "How many calories per 100g is considered high calorie?", answer: "Foods above 400 calories per 100g are classified as high energy density. Examples include nuts (550-650 cal/100g), chocolate (500-550 cal/100g), butter (717 cal/100g), and cooking oils (884 cal/100g). These foods are not inherently unhealthy — nuts and olive oil are nutritious — but they pack many calories into a small amount, so portion awareness is important." },
  { question: "How do I convert calories per 100g to calories per ounce?", answer: "Multiply calories per 100g by 0.283495 (since 1 ounce = 28.3495 grams). For example, a food with 200 calories per 100g has 200 x 0.283495 = 56.7 calories per ounce. Alternatively, divide calories per 100g by 3.527 to get calories per ounce. This calculator handles the conversion automatically for you." },
  { question: "Why do nutrition labels use per 100g instead of per serving?", answer: "Many countries require nutrition information per 100g because it provides a standardized basis for comparing foods. Serving sizes vary between brands and countries, making direct comparison difficult. Per 100g values let you compare any two foods on an equal footing. The European Union, Australia, and many other regions mandate per 100g labeling. The United States primarily uses per serving but is increasingly including per 100g data as well." }
